Identities with combinatorial proofs.
Many identities involving binomial coefficients can be proved by combinatorial means. For example, the following identity for nonnegative integers formula_64 (which reduces to (6) when "q" = 1):
can be given a double counting proof as follows. The left side counts the number of ways of selecting a subset of ["n"] = {1, 2, …, n} with at least "q" elements, and marking "q" elements among those selected. The right side counts the same parameter, because there are formula_66 ways of choosing a set of "q" marks and they occur in all subsets that additionally contain some subset of the remaining elements, of which there are formula_67
In the Pascal's rule
both sides count the number of "k"-element subsets of ["n"] with the right hand side ﬁrst grouping them into those that contain element "n" and those that do not.
The identity (9) also has a combinatorial proof. The identity reads
Suppose you have formula_70 empty squares arranged in a row and you want to mark (select) "n" of them. There are formula_71 ways to do this. On the other hand, you may select your "n" squares by selecting "k" squares from among the first "n" and formula_72 squares from the remaining "n" squares; any "k" from 0 to "n" will work. This gives
Now apply (5) to get the result.
The identity (9),
has the following combinatorial proof. The number formula_75 denotes the number of paths in a two-dimensional lattice from formula_76 to formula_77 using steps formula_78 and formula_79. This is easy to see: there are formula_80 steps in total and one may choose the formula_81 formula_79 steps. Now, replace each formula_79 step by a formula_84 step; note that there are exactly formula_81. Then one arrives at point formula_86 using steps formula_78 and formula_84. Doing this for all formula_81 between formula_90 and formula_91 gives all paths from formula_76 to formula_86 using steps formula_78 and formula_84. Clearly, there are exactly formula_96 such paths.
Sum of coefficients row.
The number of "k"-combinations for all "k", formula_97, is the sum of the "n"th row (counting from 0) of the binomial coefficients. These combinations are enumerated by the 1 digits of the set of base 2 numbers counting from 0 to formula_98, where each digit position is an item from the set of "n".
